      <div resp="part:emfr" type="translation">
        <p>
      			May Rājasiṃha <supplied reason="explanation">the lion among kings</supplied> Raṇajaya <supplied reason="explanation">the victorious one among kings</supplied> Śrībhara <supplied reason="explanation">the Fortune-bearer</supplied> Citrakārmuka <supplied reason="explanation">he whose quiver is a wonder</supplied> Ekavīra <supplied reason="explanation">the unique hero</supplied> Śivacūḍāmaṇi <supplied reason="explanation">he who has Śiva as diadem</supplied> protect the earth for long.
      		</p>
      </div>
      <div resp="part:sybr" type="translation" xml:lang="fra">
        <!--add second translator: part:emfr"-->
        <p>
          <l>Puisse Rājasiṃha, le vainqueur au combat,</l>
          <l>Celui qui apporte la prospérité, celui qui possède un arc resplendissant,</l>
          <l>Le héros unique, longtemps protéger la terre,</l>
          <l>Lui qui porte Śiva comme diadème !</l>
        </p>
      </div>
      <div type="commentary">
        <p>The same verse is found in two other inscriptions of Narasiṃhavarman II. See <ref target="INSPallava00054.xml">INSPallava00054</ref> (stanza 12) and <ref target="INSPallava00060.xml">INSPallava00060</ref> (stanza 3).</p>
      </div>
